title: Jedi Holocron modded for tealight
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I really liked Badkitty's version of the Jedi Holocron (also credit to Hambone211 for the original side panels modified by Badkitty!) with it's simple interlocking design, but for a little side project, I wanted to combine it with the really ingenious tealight adapter that MKotsamanes made for his Sith Holocron (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1194407).

I took meshmixer (after trying and failing completely with fusion 360...), and about two hours because I had no idea how to do what I wanted to get done, but here is the end result.

The whole design has been reduced from the original 10cm size down to 8cm, just because the tealights aren't too powerful, and it's more of a handholdable size for most people.

Additionally, since getting acrylic sheet in appropriate colours has become really difficult for some reason, I designed some simple 3D printable panel inserts that should be printed in your favourite translucent filament.

To make this, you'll need to print:
1x Base
1x Top
2x Side 1
2x Side 2
5x Panel insert

And then you'll want to get yourself a standard LED tealight. Yes, an electronic one. DO NOT USE A REAL CANDLE! (The correct ones are 36mm across, but I think that's basically industry standard.)

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

200 microns

Infill:

100%

Notes:

There aren't any fine details on the vertical plane, so resolution doesn't make a difference. What's important is to have a good clean surface to print on, as everything is orientated to print with the eventual outside laying flat on the bed.

I suggest printing the panel inserts with 100% infill or enough solid layers to make them solid. The top and sides are probably best built solid as well, but the base can have your preferred infill to save on material and make it lighter, if you wish.

Cleaning up any strings and giving the outer pieces a quick coat of spray paint will really bring this model to life, but it should look presentable just glued together after printing, whichever you prefer.

not good to see on image: rodholder already had lots of cracks.this is the last i own. I can't show you the others as i already dumped them I needed relatively much force to break it by holding the platform-part and using force to the side. Use 30% or more to obtain a lifetime lifesaver ^_^ History

2 Weeks ago i bought my AnetA8-Kit, to learn how 3D-printers works and with this thing in mind.Maybe just to legitimate the printer to me and my beloved gf xD. No,for real i was watching videos and reading text about fdm-printing for almost a year.
Here in germany you often have very cheap shower curtain-sets to buy as they're only two classes to buy:
either very cheap, with a nice aluminium rod and curtain, but very bad holders, or pretty expensive sets, where everything is fine,but they're just unaffordable for regular people. When you have already bought such a set, are as clumsy as me, or do have childs as me, them or you already accidentally ripped some of this cheap-ass rodholders off the wall.
Speaking for me it already happened alot. In first place, when i was mounting the first one, it already broke, while i was tightening the screw (there is just one in the middle to make it invisible.)

So i came up with this idea and got inspired by the original design and some rodholders i saw in industryplaces. I took a look into the thingiverse but found nothing suiting my needs.
After i nearly wasted one spool of filament on my way making the toughest shower-curtain-rodholder, or however this is called in english, it's finally there,
hoping to serve the community.

title: Fox-1B RadFxSat AMSAT OSCAR-91 Scale Model
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Fox-1B or RadFxSat is an amateur radio satellite constructed by AMSAT (the Radio Amateur Satellite Corporation) and launched into low Earth orbit on a Delta II rocket from Vandenberg Air Force Base on November 18, 2017. After successful on-orbit operation, it was designated AMSAT-OSCAR 91, or AO-91. Much more information about AO-91 is available at http://www.amsat.org

This is a life-size scale model of AO-91 designed for 3D printing. It is based on the actual design files for AO-91, but some difficult-to-print details have been omitted, including the antennas.

Notes:

The whole cube as a single object is a huge thing to print, and there's no way to print it cleanly without support material. STL files for the six individual faces were created to solve this problem. Each face can be printed with the flat inside surface down, and get the best results on the visible outside surfaces. Then the faces can be glued together to make the cube model.

After Printing

Glue the six faces together at right angles to make a roughly cubical model. It should be fairly obvious how they are supposed to go together.

How This Model Was Created

I started with a set of CAD files created by AMSAT team member Bob Davis to capture the actual physical design of the spacecraft. This model contained every screw (with threads modeled), the two bent sheet metal pieces that form the chassis (with holes and countersinks modeled), the six circuit boards with solar cells and other components attached, the eight machined corner pieces, and so on. It didn't contain all the internal parts of the spacecraft, but it did include many parts that would not be visible in the final printed model. The CAD model, like the spacecraft, is largely hollow and open to outside vacuum.

To make it printable, I brought the exported CAD file into Fusion 360. I eliminated most of the holes and hollowness by modeling a solid cube that matched the dimensions of the innermost visible surfaces. The cube had to be modified to preserve certain details, such as the Phillips screw heads. Some of the external objects in the CAD model (solar cells and their connections) had to be modified to actually touch or intersect with the inner surfaces. Other external objects would not have been printable and were simply deleted. Finally, all the remaining CAD objects were merged with the solid cube to create a single solid model of the satellite.

The single solid model is theoretically printable, but not very practical. To make a more practically printable design, the six faces of the cube were sliced off using construction planes to create a minimum thickness of 5mm.

title: Z Axis cal Jig for I3 Mega

description.text:
I could not fine a good way to measure accurately, and repeatable, the Z axis to set up both micro switches. I made this, I took the average distance between the X and Y 8 mm bars as my printer came, for me it was 64 mm when "home all" was done.
To use first clean up the print, then snap the wide end on the Y rail and rotate onto the X rail (with motor's turned off) adjust the Z screws by hand so the X rail just rests in the cup, with out bending or warping anything. Then adjust the long Philips screw that actuates the switch until it just makes, do the same for the other side, and repeat. Note: you may have to back off the adjustment screw to "unmake" the switch first.

Hope this helps, and I'm sure the concept will work with other printers too.

description.text:
Just wanted to design a simple hand drum. You don't need the drumstick, you could just play it with your hand, but the stick will give a different sound. A small sheet of some kind of appropriate hide is meant to be stretched over the inner ring, and then the outer ring fits snugly over it to keep the drumskin taut.

Update: added a second file with little pegs around the outer rim, so the drumskin could be pulled up around these after the outer rim is put in place to further secure it and give the added aesthetic of whatever your drumskin material is on the outer rim. You could either put a small slice in the material and attach like the pegs are buttons, or you could cut strings into the excess and tie these to the pegs. ALTERNATE ENDING DRUM.

Update TWO: So I keep tweaking this. I found out what the dimensions of the print bed will be on the printer I'm getting (eventually, I'm waiting on the Obsidian from Kodama and they're still working out production kinks). I wanted to actually be able to print my drum and have it be a size that would fit in the bed so I tweaked about in TinkerCAD again and made sure this would do the trick-- which necessitated removing the handle and printing it as a separate piece to be glued into the hole after the fact. I also lengthened both the handle and the drumstick for more comfortable holding and I quite liked the effect to the drumstick head. This 3rd version is probably the most workable. I'm not sure if the rings will fit together the way they're supposed to, I wasn't sure if I should make it flush with the outer ring to really keep the skin taut (have to tap in place with a hammer I guess) or if I should leave space for the skin between... anyway what I ended up doing is duplicating the inner ring and then "cutting" it out of the inside of the outer ring so I know it exactly fits. Whether or not I can force it to fit with a drumskin between remains to be seen.

description.text:
I was tired of the scattered toothbrush heads on our bathroom sink and decided to design something to fix it. There are many other options already on Thingiverse, one of them I'm going to print out to see if it's better, but I wanted to learn more about sketches in Fusion 360 and this was as good an excuse as any.

I also printed an insert that can be used for the toothbrush holder holes. The holes can hold the brushes as is, and it works fine. But if you want them to sit on pegs and be a little less wobbly, the insert should work for that. I made them a separate component since printing them in the orientation that makes the entire stand strong will make the pegs flimsy and likely to snap.

You'll notice 2 versions, sonicare.stl and sonicare-short.stl. We have a little dropper bottle to hold our tooth drops, so I designed that into the stand. The sonicare-short.stl file omits this feature since most people won't need it, so that is most likely the file you will want to use. Buckyballs are popular shapes for geodesic domes.
All the edges have the same length and only one type of vertex.
The each vertex connects two hexagons with one pentagon.
A real dome is going to be more complicated because you will want more floor area than one face.
Joining or extending balls is harder again because most faces are at strange angles.
Here is one way to add an extension.
There are simpler ways but this keeps the faceted look of the dome.

description.text: Parametric length arm for a RAM vehicular mounting system, which goes between two rubberized balls - http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ram_Mounts This item is ment to replace (functionally) the arm of a RAP-B-166-2U set - As such, it works on 1" diameter ball joints and the system is rated for support of 5 pounds or less. Edit: Attributed Catarina Mota's hexagon function the way I should have from the beginning. Functionally, the file's the same. Changed 4/12/14 to allow the option of a bolt/wingnut combo at each end instead of just one in the middle . Changed 6/8/14 to offer a range of bolt size options. Took off 'work in progress' tag 4/20/2016 - Lots of downloads and relatively little feedback - I'm going to call it done.

The file is only one half - Print one side with a nut trap, one without, use a bolt and a wing nut to join them as in the picture.
(Note: Pic is a M5-.8 x 50mm bolt and matching wing nut - The SCAD file supports bolts in the metric sizes M4,M5,M6 and M8 as well as SAE sizes 8,10 and 1/4" - I suggest using a bolt at least 40mm or 1 1/2" long . ) Strongly suggest using ABS if you are using this for a car dash - PLA versions to date have all warped badly and become unusable, but ABS prints have held up for me so far.

description.text:
Recently stumbled upon this terrific set of X-Axis ends for a P3Steel printer. (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2088585) Since the P3Steel uses the same 17MM spacing on the leadscrew and vertical smooth rods I wanted to print these for my old beater Tronxy P802M. The only problem is horizontal rod spacing. Most printers like the Anet and P3Steel have 45mm spacing between the X-axis horizontal rods. The Zonestar and Tronxy are 44mm. This would be a problem as I want to use my original carriage.

After looking at the above linked Thing I see the designer was kind enough to include the STEP files for his parts. This was just what I needed. After importing the STEP files into Fusion 360 modifying the rod spacing was a snap.

title: Teletype paper tape splicing and alignment guide jig

description.text:
If you are into vintage computing then you may find this little jig useful. It facilitates the cutting of sharp, straight cuts across 1" wide 8-level ASCII Teletype paper tape.
This makes it easier to trim, splice or join sections of paper tape for repair so it lessens jamming and tearing when run through a paper tape reader such as an ASR33, PC05, OP-80A, EECO CNC or whatever other paper tape reader you have.

Use
Place the tape to be cut onto the jig with the centre blade slot where you require cutting. Press down firmly until the tape feed sprocket holes are seated properly on the sprocket pins. Using a single edge razor blade positioned in the centre slot (make sure it is SHARP) press on one edgeand then right through. It should give a crisp snapping noise as it cuts. You could also use an X-acto #11 blade in a hobby knife.

Generating
The OpenSCAD parametric script is included so you can tweak it if you like. For instance to make it longer, just bump the PINS value. Although a 5-level Baudot RTTY paper tape will fit fine on the guide as it is, you can change the LEVEL variable from 8 (ASCII 8-level) to 5 (Baudot 5-level) specifically if you desire.

Printing
PLA is ideal. Infill was 25% but could be anywhere from there up to 100%. Printed with brim only, no raft. I touched the pins and cutting groove with a black permanent marker to improve locating visibility

Making Teletype paper tape without a punch
If you don't have an actual vintage paper tape punch you can use a home stencil cutting machine along with my PTAP2DXF program to make paper tape that is fully functional (as used in this thing's photo).
For more info visit https://github.com/1944GPW/ptap2dxf

description.text:
Lithophane Lamp

This is a lithophane lamp shade I designed to work with this lamp: Aukey Table Lamp

The lamp shown in photos is one I made with 8 lithophane images of (mostly) tropical fruits. Aside from the 8 lithophanes, the lamp consists of two support rings, and an upper surface. Follow the directions below to make your own.

Also, I included the G-code files I used with my MP Select Mini. You can import my slicer settings into Cura by going to Preferences > Profiles > Import and choosing the G-code file.

Lithophane photo panels

Choose a photo and crop it to a perfect square. I did this in Photos on Mac, but it could be done in an photo editing software. It’s important that it has equal width and height. It may also help to increase the contrast a bit depending on your photo, but not necessary.

Use this awesome site to generate a lithophane panel (STL) from your image. Here are the settings I used:

  • Model: Choose "Outer Curve"
  • Model Settings:
    Maximum Size (MM): 87
    Thickness (MM): 2
    Border (MM): 2
    Thinnest Layer (MM): 0.8
    Vectors Per Pixel: 10 (could set this lower for a smaller STL)
    Base/Stand Depth: 0
    Curve: 90
  • Image Settings:
    Positive Image
    Mirror Image Off
    Flip Image Off
    Manual Refresh
    Repeat X Count 1
    Repeat Y Count 1
    Mirror Repeat Off
    Flip Repeat Off

Repeat for all your images.

For the best quality, I strongly recommend printing the lithophane panels in high quality (I used 0.0875 mm layer height), 100% infill, standing upright, and with the z-axis seam set so that each layer starts on the edge of the image. I've included my G-code files which you can import into Cura to use as an example.

Support rings and upper surface.

The lower and middle rings can both be printed in lower quality (I used 0.175 mm layer height) and without support.

The upper surface is probably best printed upside-down. My print bed isn't perfectly level, so I printed the upper surface right side up with supports and got nice results.

Assembly

Clean any excess plastic or rough edges off the lithophane panels. Four lithophane panels should fit into the outer groove of the lower ring, completing a circle. These will be the panels for the lower part of the lamp shade. I had to trim a bit of plastic off the bottom of the lithophanes and sand the side edges just a little (it’s a tight fit).

Fit the middle ring on to the top of the same four panels. Once it is perfect, use a few drops of super glue to permanently attach the lithophane panels into the groove of the lower and middle rings.

Place the other four lithophane panels into the top groove of the middle ring. Then fit the upper surface onto the top of these panels. Again, lock it in place with super glue.

The lamp shade should fit perfectly on this lamp. It is designed to be snug, so you may need to sand/trim the inner rings a little if it won’t slide onto the lamp.

Links

  • Lamp: Aukey Table Lamp
  • Lithophane generator: Image to Lithophane
  • Tinkercad:
    • Upper Surface
    • Middle Ring
    • Lower Ring

Update Dec 2017

  • Added Upper Surface V2, which has a stronger groove edge and a slightly wider groove for easier assembly.
  • Added Gap Filler which can be glued to the inside between the lithophane panels to keep light from coming through between the panels.

description.text:
Put the ten pieces together to form a pyramid. Harder than it looks. Completed puzzle looks good on a shelf.

Not as nice as the wood and steel original, but cheaper and fun to make.

For a challenge, print the ball pieces whole. Otherwise, for an easy print, do what I did and print the balls in halves and assemble.

Wood filament for the board and metal filament for the balls would look nice, if you have some laying around.

While you're here, check out my other puzzle:
Identical Twins Puzzle

If you can't solve this and want to give up, you can message me on Thingiverse, and I'll send you the link to the Youtube video with the solution.

Choosing the right model:
Since you use filament for aligning the halves when you assemble them (and to provide strength against sheering), pick the right model for your filament size. Print the 1.75mm halves if you have 1.75mm filament and the 3mm halves if you have 3mm filament.

Instructions:
Print 10 whole pieces or 20 half pieces. Unless you have awesome cooling, make sure that you print more than one piece at a time (probably at least 4).

Insert filament in the holes and cut to form small pegs on one side, then glue and snap on the other side.

There is a small fillet on the rim of the ball halves to allow for first layer squish. There is a significant fillet on the holes to prevent the first layer squish from shrinking the holes. This keeps you from having to drill out the holes. I suppose, depending on your slicer and printer, you still might have to do some drilling, but let's hope for the best.

Put the glue in a small bead all the way around the filament "pegs", then snap together and hold or clamp.

title: Kit set BB gun pellet trap (Ressetable)

description.text:
This is a pellet trap for BB guns. The triangle point of the target spinner should( in theory) catch in the small slit on the front plate when the small cicular target is hit. The big rectangular target can then be shot to reset the trap back to the original cicular target. The targets can easily be exchanged for your own designs (they just need a small slit in them). This is my entry for the Make magazine competition:
http://blog.makezine.com/archive/2010/04/makerbot_giveaway.html EDIT: I have updated the model (STL files only) so that the BB's will not be deflected back towards the shooter, when firing through the bottom target.

The parts should be able to be printed and then assembled with the holes and studs aligning. As this is my first ever 3d printing model, can you please let me know if it is not possible to print parts of the design. 
Or if the design does not work, I can easily adjust the angle the triangular point is on, so it requires less force to engage the rectangular reset target.
I made a mistake and thought that the top plane is normal to the Z-direction in solidworks, but unfortuantely it is not! Therefore the STL files are shown in the wrong plane to be printed. Hopefully you can rotate the STL files 90 degrees (about the x axis), yourself before printing (If not, please let me know).

title: Qi Charge Base for Motorola Nexus 6

description.text:
This is a charging base designed for hanging on a wall. It is designed for use with the CHOETECH Qi Wireless Charge Pad, available here:

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B013AB63YW

The base has a "foot" which helps position the phone over the charger appropriately, and two pressure "arms" that retain the phone while it's hanging on the wall. In the back, there's a slot for the USB cable to thread through.

When I printed this in PLA, the charger stayed put with a simple press-fit, though it would be easy enough to stick it in place using some double-sided / foam tape. There will be a bit of clearance between the phone and the charger, so there's room to customize it some.

Printer:

Off-Brand Prusa i3 (from kit)

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.4

Infill:

20% - doesn't matter much

Notes:

I printed with 0.185mm layer height and 200C hotend to improve layer adhesion as much as possible. Then, I used 5 top/bottom layers and 3 perimeters to make it reasonably strong.

These settings are more than enough for the stresses put on this charger.

WARNINGS:

  • The STL appears upside down in my Slic3r, so I had to rotate it over X by 180 degrees.
  • If you don't rotate, you'll need supports.
  • If you print it on its back, you'll weaken the retaining arms.

Smoothing

I filed out the insides of the retaining arms for a smoother fit. Your printer might produce a cleaner result than mine, so YMMV.

Also, since I printed without supports, I had to sand down the bottom fillets a bit (they had sagged just a bit due to the high hotend temp).

title: 4X5 Ground Glass Holder for Large Format Camera

description.text: I wanted a way to demonstrate, at the 2014 Seattle Mini Maker Faire, how a pinhole camera projects an image onto film. The PINH5AD is a large format pinhole camera I designed to work with a 4X5 sheet film holder. This frame replaces the film holder for the purpose of visualizing the (inverted and rotated) image formed through the pinhole. Because the image will be faint (pinholes are, by definition, small apertures), some kind of hood or drape will be necessary to block ambient light. My testing suggests that only the brightest light sources are resolved using a pinhole. Alas. For an example of what this looks like, see the "MAKES" section. --> You've seen old-time "view cameras" in movies - this is exactly how the "view" is composed before the film is exposed after swapping the ground glass for a loaded film holder. This will fit any camera that uses a standard 4X5 film holder. The glass plate is held precisely 3mm from the face of the holder, duplicating the position of the film. In a pinhole camera there is no one focal distance, but for lensed cameras, maintaining correct focal distance is crucial for composing and focusing the scene you want to capture.

All other related content (photographs, videos, and verbiage such as contained in "Description" or "Instructions" ) are excluded from this license. with all rights reserved, unless specifically available for download This notice constitutes a clarification, not a change, to licensing for this design.

You will also need:
8 - 3M x 8 machine screws (or similar 1/8" hardware)
Appropriate tap for threads The retainer is intended to be screwed to the holder, sandwiching the plate of ground glass in place. If the glass should break (don't drop it!) the glass can be replaced. The glass plate I used measured a nominal 122 x 100mm. I designed-in a little tolerance for the glass, but still needed to remove a sliver of material from both ends to get the glass to fit nicely. I drilled out the retainer holes and tapped the holder holes (from underneath) for 3mm screws. It should go without saying, but I'll say it: plastic threads are not very strong! Use a light touch when assembling this. For maximum accuracy, print with a layer height that factors evenly into 1mm; I used 0.25mm layer height. PS, let these parts cool on the printer bed before popping them off - any prying while warm may irreparably warp them. Ask me how I know this.

title: Anemone BC Base Tentacle (BigClown Base Station Case)

description.text:
Anemone BC Base Tentacle is a 3D printable case for BigClown Base Station.

It is part of the open and free #anemoneCloud Platform, but it can be used completely standalone as well.

When used inside the Anemone Platform the Tentacle could be used as a DYI Open Hardware device which can be easily connected to cloud APIs, mobile app and/or other tentacles of open hardware devices. All this completely free of any charge. More documentation about how to use this Tentacle in the Anemone Ecosystem can be found at: Anemone Docs.

When used outside the Anemone Platform it can be used as a cute case for your BigClown Base Station - the BigClown Base Station can be assembled from the following BigClown modules:

  • The Core Module - https://shop.bigclown.com/core-module/
  • The Power Module - https://shop.bigclown.com/power-module/
  • The Base Module - https://shop.bigclown.com/base-module/ (but the bottom part of this case is replacing it)
  • USB-A to micro-USB cable

You can add up to three BigClown Tags to measure stuff and plug two of them in to the Power Module and the third one can be plugged into the Core Module.

I am not the sole author of this thing or of the Anemone Project. Anemone Tentacle has been created as a team effort of our great team at Juicymo and our client. See more info about who is behind this here.

Tentacle Visualization can be found at YouTube

Anemone BC Base Tentacle case is LEGO compatible!

#anemoneCloud

Notes:

The Anemone Tentacle 3D case is available either as .stl files of 3 individual components:

  • The Bottom Part (Anemone_BC_Base_Bottom.stl)
  • The Walls (Anemone_BC_Base_Top.stl)
  • The Top Buttons (Anemone_BC_Base_Buttons.stl)

Or as a ready-to-print .stl file with all components (to be printed all at once):

  • Anemone_BigClown_Base_Tentacle.stl

In addition to the .stl ready-to-print file you can download a exported gcode file for the Prusa i3 MK2 3D Printer with ABS filament setting. We have used this gcode file to print our version of Anemone BC Base Tentacle on Kanárek (Prusa i3 MK2S Original 3D Printer).

Recommended print settings

The Anemone Tentacle case is optimized to be printed in ABS (but we have tested printing with PLA too and it works well).

We have used the open source Prusa Slic3r for slicing the .stl files into .gcode. The Prusa Slic3r has few advantages compared to the original Slic3r (like better supports and more).

Anemone Tentacle case looks awesome even on low print settings - which looks nice with a semi-transparent filament.

Global settings

  • Filament: ABS 1.75mm
  • Extruder Temperature: 255°C
  • Heat-bed Temperature: 100°C
  • Layer height: 0.35mm
  • First layer height: 0.15mm
  • Perimeters: 1
  • Infill density: 20%
  • Infill pattern: Cubic
  • Skirt: 1
  • Brim: 4mm
  • Support: Yes

Tips and Tricks

  • When printing with ABS you HAVE TO to use the heated bed!

After printing the second part (The Walls) needs to be cleaned of supports.

When done you can assemble the Anemone BC Base Tentacle case.

The Anemone IoT Platform Story

The original idea for Anemone was to create a simple Open Hardware device which would be able to send information to the cloud (or internet) and which will be very easy to use for others.

Over time, the idea expanded a little. And we have ended up creating not just the Open Hardware device itself (we call it a Tentacle) but 3D printable case, cloud web application and even mobile application for iOS and Android as well.

And now we in fact have quite a nice ecosystem. Not with many apps right now, but it is ready to use! And that is where we need your help ;)

With Anemone, you can create a cloud enabled IoT apps in a very easy way and get them hosted for free in the Anemone Cloud. Or you can just print the Tentacle Case and upload a picture of it to the I made it section. Our Anemone BC Base Tentacle case is the very first 3D printed case for the BigClown Base Station Module.

And you can use it freely even completely outside the Anemone platform too.

So enjoy! ;)

I am not the sole author of this thing or of the Anemone Project. Anemone Tentacle has been created as a team effort of our great team at Juicymo and our client. See more info about who is behind this here.
CCSS
This lesson can be used as a semestral work for any subject featuring electronics, programming and 3D printing.

In this project you will learn how to assemble and program a working open hardware device with a cute 3D Printed case.

The Tentacle can be used as part of the open and free Anemone Platform, or completely standalone. The project plan is divided accordingly.

• Preparation - Put all required components together
  • 3D Print a Tentacle case
  • Assemble your Tentacle

• Understand how Anemone Platform works
  • Understand different types of Anemone Tentacles
  • Connect your Tentacle to the Anemone Cloud
  • Understand how the Flow and Flow Editor works

• Read the BigClown documentation for your Core Module
  • Program your Core Module as you see fit ;)

The following components are needed for your BigClown Base Tentacle:
  • 1x The Core Module
  • 1x The Power Module
  • 1x The Base Module (but the bottom part of this case is replacing it)
  • 1x USB-A to micro-USB cable
    • You can add up to 3 individual sensor tags as needed.

• 3D Printing
  • Electronics
  • Programming
3D Printing Setup: 30min + 3D Printing: 3h + Programming: 5h = 8h 30min

• You need to have all the required components
  • You should 3D print a case
  • You should assemble the case
    • And you are ready for connecting your Tentacle to Anemone Ecosystem.

Anemone BC Base Tentacle can be used in a tasks like "Creation of a cloud enabled Open Hardware Device". An example assessment for students could be:

Your task is to create a working Anemone BC Base Tentacle open hardware device. Your task is the following:

  1. 3D print a Tentacle case
  2. Assemble the Tentacle electronics (see the Materials Needed section)
  3. Program the device (a detailed instructions are available when you will create a new Tentacle in the Anemone Platform - you can sign in for free)
The student assessment is a success when:
  • Students were able to construct a working Anemone BC Base Tentacle device and they were able to communicate with a Anemone Cloud Flow.

    • Students should work in teams of two.

-Moved magnet holes closer to base for firmer hold on gantry
-Made caps larger so they fit in holes better
-Changed the look a bit, I wasn't digging the boxiness.


I know there are plenty of these out there, but I wasn't perfectly happy with any I saw, plus I designed mine specifically around the dial indicator I picked up here.
http://www.harborfreight.com/1-inch-travel-machinists-dial-indicator-623.html
There are two tiny slots that you can slide small .25" magnets into, put the small caps on the backside and glue everything in place. Helps to ensure that the mount stays firmly on the gantry.
Having this little setup has dramatically eased the leveling process for me

Rep 2 PLA, 2 wall 10% infill
Printed no supports. EZPZ. When using run whatever leveling script you use on your rep2 to bring the bed/head into the correct position, adjust the head as normal directly over one of the springs, then use the dial indicator directly over that position to mark your "level point". Exit out of the leveling script then just move the gantry over the other screw/spring levelers and ensure they are leveled to the same point on your dial indicator.
You can then check your bed all over to ensure its leveled accurately. This will also help to point out the flaws of the stock acrylic bed if you are still using that.

description.text:
This is a detailed 1:1 scale model of the M-300 Claymore from the Mass effect games. It is roughly 470 mm long or just over 1.5 ft. Modelled from multiple reference pictures in google sketchup. My friend who will be attending a convention this fall requested this item for his costume. A week and a half later this is what we have. "The Claymore used to be a hard-hitting but poor-selling shotgun due to kickback problems snapping the arms of anyone but krogan firing the weapon." - Mass Effect 3 Reference images retrieved from:
http://masseffect.wikia.com/wiki/M-300_Claymore
http://troodon80.deviantart.com/ All Credits to EA/Bioware/All applicable parties involved in the creation of the Mass Effect Saga.

Updated: Lettering on left side was backwards from inversion, fixed.
The sketchup model is segmented into many sub components which can fit within an 8 by 8 by 8 inch (200 mm)build envelope (Most are considerably less.) All parts other than the handle are then cut in half so as to print as flat bottomed pieces which can be glued or melted together. Disclaimers:
  • Not entirely accurate to images, minor artistic changes have been make. Ex: Screw heads, sizes, spacing, raised lettering, etc.
  • This is a large project. I estimate it to take almost 2 kgs of plastic on a low infill setting (10-15%) and almost 4 days of printing.
  • I do not have a 3d printer yet, though I plan to print this when my printer arrives in August, thus this has not been tested.
  • I am mildly disappointed in my trigger design. Well it is accurate to the image, it will not be particularly function and I welcome redesigns.
    • Warning:
    Even if this may just look like a toy, it still bares the semblance of a gun, despite it being a fictional one. Be careful, do not misuse this, and for added safety paint the barrel orange. This identifies it as a fake. I will remove this model should Thingiverse request me to however it is, once again, not a real weapon. Many other replicas are currently uploaded to Thingiverse. REVISION 19th/12/2012: This model was originally taken down however upon further review and a few e-mails a representative from thingiverse agreed that this does not violate the terms of the policy and returned this model to its full statues.

This is a double-threaded adapter to screw a camera module (C-mount 1"-32 UN 2A) on top of the trinocular Amscope extension tube (M26/0.75) you can find on models such as the SM-3TZ-54S.

The OpenSCAD file is available and all dimensions are configurable, in case you need to adjust something. It's based on polyScrewThread_r1 library (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8796).
There is a "correction" factor of 1.005 in the file because the printed thread was a bit smaller than specified. If you've problems with the print, check the outer diameter of the M26 thread, it should be about 25.85 (comprised between 25.73 and 25.97).

To install it, unscrew the silver tube from the extension tube and screw the adapter instead.
Screw it gently to its maximum.
Beware both threads are very similar so take care to put it in the right direction.
The large thread is the one that goes into the extension tube.
The small thread is the C-mount.
Once settled, adjust focus for your eyes, then switch to the camera and adjust camera focus with the extension tube, so now you can get both eyes and camera focused simultaneously.
To adjust the image orientation, free the base of the extension tube (there is a small screw on the outskirt) and rotate it.

description.text:
I've been making one of Kyo's Sphinx CNC routers for myself (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1741813), and I thought I'd share some of the files I've made to assist with mounting and setup for anyone else who's doing the same thing.

Rear PSU Mounting:
The Meanwell LRS-350-24 PSU is a great fit for this build. I've included "PSU Support" for the rear mount. I've used some M4 x 8mm countersunk machine screws to mount to the PSU, and some M5 x 20mm machine screws for the mount to the board (the image shows M5 x 25mm with a spacer).

Front PSU Mounting:
I've gone with this thing:https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2440784 which was pretty close. Again I've used M4 x 8mm countersunk machine screws into the PSU, and I've added a little block to the side (see below) for a more secure mount. And an additional block on top to help secure the power connector (see also below). That's secured with M5 x 25mm machine screws.

PSU Front Mount Block:
I've used this to secure the front of the PSU cover to the board. I have some M5 Nylok nuts burried inside, and I've used 3.5 x 14mm woodscrews to mount it to the baseboard.

Power Connector Adapter :
I used this IEC 320 C14 chassis mount: https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B017VUBJMY/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 being mains electric I wanted it to be secure so I drew up this mount block, which has M5 Nylok nuts on the inside, and some M5 x 10mm machine screws to hold it down. I've used some Loctite 60 seconds all purpose glue to stick this bit to the cover. Works great for both PLA and PETG.

Phoenix Mount:
If you've followed the reccomendation from Kyo in the electronics video, you've gone with this controller board from Phoenix CNC: https://www.tindie.com/products/PhoenixCNC/phoenix-usb-cnc-controller-with-pwm-output/

I can absolutely reccomend it - well built and does exactly what it says out of the box. I've drawn up a mount for it, I've used 3.5 x 14mm countersunk woodscrews to mount both the board to the mount, and the mount to the base board.

Controls Mount:
I've ordered some nice metal looking buttons for when I build a custom enclosure, but for now I've used this mount, to support these cheap buttons from Maplin: https://www.maplin.co.uk/p/125v-1a-push-to-make-switch-red-fh59p (that's the red, they do the black as well). Again I've used 3.5 x 14 countersunk woodscrews to secure this to the base board.

Base Foot:
Just a simple foot secured with an M5 x 25mm machine screw and nylok nut.

I've still got to lace up the wiring and make it look pretty - but if I don't post these now, I'll just get distracted by my next project :-)

But this only one option how you power it.

print_settings.Notes:: Step six: Enjoy having an apparently solid brick with something valuable inside it.

description.text:
Read the printing instructions carefully and follow them.

The end result of this thing is a plastic "brick" 5x25x40 mm, with a hollow interior where you can place important stuff (piece of paper with some code/password/secret for example) with no possibility of getting that thing out without clearly destroying the plastic brick. It won't stop anyone from getting to the inside, but you will know someone has been there. Also, it is not obvious to anyone that there is something inside at all, unless you tell them. It looks like any plastic brick. Because the design is so simple, you may easily copy the cover part (just 1x25x40 mm flat plate) and add something like a domino pattern or whatever to make the brick look even less suspicious.

Notes:

This is IMPORTANT!!!!

Step four should be prepared at the same time as step two is prepared, so you can print it as soon as possible after the first print is done, to make sure the layer adhesion is as good as possible! Hot plastic on somewhat hot plastic is better than hot plastic on cold plastic.

Step one: Make sure your slicer has a setting to "begin printing at Z-height ..." I use Simplify3D which has this feature.

Step two: Print "tpcon_base" and "tpcon_inner" at the same time, but make sure to have "tpcon_base" centered on the print bed! No rafts should be necessary, but if you do use one, make sure to take this into account for any height instructions to follow.

Step three: As soon as this first print is done, remove "tpcon_inner" (the smaller piece) from the print bed, place whatever valuable item you have inside "tpcon_base" and place "tpcon_inner" over it, making sure the top of both parts align (well, +/-0.2 mm should be ok).

Step four: Make a new print in the slicing software and import "tpcon_cover". Using custom positioning controls, place this centered in X/Y and +4.05 or 4.10 mm in Z (just to make sure it doesn't collide with the "tpcon_base" that now sits on the print bed), so that it hangs in mid air. Set your printer to not print any raft or anything like that, and to START PRINTING AT Z=4.05.

Step five: Start this print and make sure all goes as planned ("tp_cover" printing right on top of the "tp_base" that already stands on the bed).

Step six: Enjoy having an apparently solid brick with something valuable inside it.
